Wash and dry produce. Roughly chop @peanuts{1/2%ounce}. Trim, peel, and thinly slice
@carrot{3%ounce} on a diagonal. Halve, core, and thinly slice @bell pepper{1}(thinly sliced)
into strips. Trim and remove strings from @sugar snap peas{4%ounce}. Peel and mince or
grate @garlic{1%clove} and @ginger{1%thumb}.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine @sesame dressing{1.5%ounce}, @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce},
and half the @ponzu sauce{12%milliliters} (you'll use the rest later).

Heat a #large nonstick pan{} over medium-high heat. Add peanuts, @sugar{1%tsp}, and
@water{2%TBSP}. Cook, stirring often, until water has evaporated and peanuts are coated
and lightly toasted, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #small bowl{}. Wipe out pan.

Pat @pork chops{12%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}. Season lightly with @salt{} and
@pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in pan used for peanuts over medium-high heat. Add
pork; cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per side.

> If pork begins to brown too quickly, reduce heat to medium.

Transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest for at least ~{5%minutes}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for pork over medium-high heat; add carrot and bell
pepper. Cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add snap peas, ginger, and garlic. Cook until lightly browned and tender,
~{2-3%minutes} more.

Stir in remaining ponzu and @butter{1%tablespoon} until combined. Season with salt and
pepper to taste. Turn off heat.

Thinly slice pork crosswise.

Divide stir-fry and pork between plates. Top pork with sesame chili sauce. Garnish with
candied peanuts and serve.